6:
Phew, you've got the stuff! I'm
surprised that old piece of metal
could dish out as much damage as
a beamsaber!
9:
Having a beamsaber WOULD be
pretty cool though...
12:
Anyway, it was nothing compared to
you. You're like a one-woman army!
16:
She's just trigger happy. You
wouldn't believe how much we
spend on ammo every—
19:
That's why we're so glad to have you
guys around this time!
22:
I was able to save a hefty bit this
time thanks to your help, so
everything tonight's on me!
30:
Excuse me! You, the synthetic! Could
we get tonight's special for four?
42:
They're more like... machines. Think
of them as super convenient
sentient furniture.
46:
Sentient furniture?! I suppose they're
not too different from magical
familiars, yet... Hmm...
49:
They're bound to the will of the
corporations that produced them.
Drones created to be used and then
cast aside.
53: That's life without free will for you.
56:
Only free spirits like myself can tell
the monotony of everyday life here
to bite the big one and take control
of their own destinies!
60:
Looks like the main dish is here! Oh
man, you guys are in for a treat!
62:
Here you are. One SoyMate variety
plate.
66:
Is this... food? It looks more like a pile
of mush.
69:
SoyMate is produced from soy
beans and contains all the nutrients
you'll need, at a fraction of the cost
of real meat or vegetables.
73:
If you had some cybernetic eyes or
something, you could alter its
appearance with AR.
77:
Cybernetic... eyes? What are those,
some sort of glasses?
80:
Not exactly. See my left eye? All
prosthetic. In this world, you can
upgrade or replace any part of
yourself—eyes, limbs, brains, you
name it.
86:
Using machines to enhance your
body?
89:
Yep! Bionics, to be specific. Pretty
much everyone does it around here.
92:
Exception being those upper crust
elites—they're mostly all natural. We
call them organics. They think
they're SOOOO fancy.
95:
They use genome enhancements
and nanomachines to alter their
bodies instead. Costs WAY more
than clunky bionics.
99:
To be honest, I've been hiding my
surprise from it all—your unmodified
bodies, your primitive weapons.
104:
Different strokes for different folks, I
guess.
108:
This tastes like... nothing. It's
flavorless mush.
111:
Unfortunately, AR doesn't change
how it tastes or feels going in.
116:
Hmm... How about this, then?
Stewed chicken and tomato soup.
127: This flavor... it tastes like real food!
130:
That, my friend, was AdTaste. Flavor
for the masses!
132:
What you ate just now WAS an
advertisement! Tired of plain old
SoyMate? Add all kinds of flavors
and textures through the marketing
power of AdTaste.
136:
I've not seen such sorcery... How
does it work?
139:
The ad sends electrical signals to
your mouth, replicating the food's
flavor and texture. Your brain can't
tell the difference.
143:
So even if you're all organic, you can
still "taste" the flavor. Make sense?
147:
Sight, sound, smell, taste, and touch.
Not only your senses, but your
emotions, and even your memories.
151:
All sensations can be enjoyed—for
the right price. And the corporations
all know this.
156:
Wow... I've never seen anything like
it! As a chef, I have a few doubts, but
it really is amazing, huh?
160:
Choose a flavor, any flavor! It's on
me, remember?
168:
You want one too, Love? I'll get you
the same one as mine.
171:
Please be more responsible with
your funds.
175:
Hey, you can't put a price on
friendship, am I right?
181:
I suppose you're right. I'll have one of
the cheaper ones then.
186: That's more like it! And thanks.
192:
Now that THAT'S settled, let's talk
about your endgame here.
195:
Corporations in this city are
generally separated into two groups.
198:
Noxel Group and AltMeme. Most
people choose either one side or the
other.
202:
As a reward for our work, I've
received data from an informant
about the man that attacked you.
203:
He's with one of Noxel Group's
leading distributors: DayAndNight.
Also known as DAN.
207:
There's no reason for the top brass
to move directly unless they've been
ordered to by the corporation itself.
210:
And so I'd say our best bet for
finding this World Flipper is
somewhere within DAN.
214:
Thing is, their facilities are MASSIVE.
Where would we even start?
219:
I would imagine it's somewhere...
here.
223:
The DAN Distribution Control Center,
huh? Sounds like a good place to
start if you ask me.
228:
So our objective is to infiltrate their
facilities?
231:
You got it. Fortunately for us, we
have a hacker prodigy on our side.
240:
Pretty pleeeeease? It would make
things so much easier.
244:
I understand you wish to help your
new friends here, but crossing a
corporation is never a good idea.
250:
It's not like that! If what they're
saying is true, then we'll finally get to
see a real sky!
257:
I don't remember partnering up with
you for something so pointless.
263: Yeah? Fine then! I'll do it without you!
268:
Is that so? Then we have nothing
more to speak of.
272: Sorry. That got a bit ugly, didn't it?
275:
N-not at all! I mean, um, are you
sure you want to do this for us?
281:
It's fine. I can handle this much on
my own, at least.
286:
So what is the plan to infiltrate DAN
now?
289:
There's always a back door for this
type of thing.
293:
Yeesh, I don't know if I like the looks
of this place.
297:
The corporate enforcers don't patrol
the slums—the people here don't
have money, so they don't see a
reason to protect it.
299:
But people aren't the only denizens
of the slums.
304:
Uh... What are these things?
Monsters?
309:
Mutants. Not only do they stink, but
they'll gobble you up if you're not
careful.
310:
And judging by their attitude, it looks
like we'll have to get past them the
hard way!
